{
  "texts": [
    "(4.11)The data {x i, w i } that define the two covering maps Γ and Γ are the same and so, if the {z i } are such that a covering map exists, we anticipate an equivalence of definitions between (4.6) and ( 4.11) such that Γ = Γ in the discrete set of covering maps.",
    "As such, we will often drop the labels and refer to the covering map simply as Γ unless we want to emphasise the definition.",
    "This equivalence can be seen from considering the bosonization of the free fields (2.19), where ξ -= -e -ϕ 1 -iκ 1 and we interpret ζ -= e -ϕ 2 -iκ 2 as a formal expression that inverts ξ + = e ϕ 2 +iκ 2 [15],ξ + ζ -= 1.",
    "(4.12)It then becomes clear that Γ(z) = Γ(z) from e -Σ = -ξ -ζ -.",
    "We therefore deduce that our proof using e -Σ is morally equivalent to that given in the literature, but in practice, could be considered more efficient."
  ]
}